<div class="page">
  <div class="hero">
    <div class="hero-portrait"><img src="Assets/Personas/mark.png" alt="Mark"></div>
    <div class="hero-text">
      <div class="hero-eyebrow">Hearts and Minds &middot; a patient journey</div>
      <h1 class="hero-title">Mark&apos;s journey.<br>The phone that doesn&apos;t ring.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">Mark is 65, a retired teacher, and lives with his wife. Last year he was diagnosed with low-grade prostate cancer (CPG&nbsp;2) and chose Active Surveillance &mdash; active monitoring rather than immediate treatment, per NICE NG131. He sees his consultant urologist every six months. Between those visits, his PSA is what stands watch.</p>
      <p class="hero-source">Built from the model&apos;s PSA-AS configuration: the clinician-initiated pattern, told from the patient&apos;s side. Year 1 status: prospective.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="ribbon">
    <a href="#act1"><div class="ribbon-num">1</div><div class="ribbon-label">The diagnosis he lives with</div></a>
    <a href="#act2"><div class="ribbon-num">2</div><div class="ribbon-label">His consultant orders</div></a>
    <a href="#act3"><div class="ribbon-num">3</div><div class="ribbon-label">Kit out, sample back</div></a>
    <a href="#act4"><div class="ribbon-num">4</div><div class="ribbon-label">Living on surveillance</div></a>
  </div>

  <div class="stage" id="act1">
    <div class="stage-side"><div class="stage-number">1</div><div class="stage-bar"></div></div>
    <div class="stage-main">
      <div class="scene"><img src="Assets/mark-stage1.png" alt="Mark and his wife with the consultant, talking through the surveillance plan" onerror="this.closest('.scene').style.display='none'"><div class="scene-cap">The diagnosis, and the choice to watch it closely rather than treat it now.</div></div>
      <div class="stage-eyebrow">The diagnosis he lives with</div>
      <h2 class="stage-title">Watching, not fighting. That was the choice. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="mark-a1"></span></h2>
      <p class="stage-body">Low-grade prostate cancer grows slowly, and for men like Mark the evidence says watch it carefully rather than treat it immediately &mdash; treatment has costs of its own. Active Surveillance means sustained vigilance: regular PSA tests, watching the trend for any rise that would change the plan. <strong>The test is routine. What it stands guard over is not.</strong></p>
      <p class="stage-body">The old shape of that vigilance: a trip to hospital phlebotomy for every routine draw &mdash; car park, waiting room, needle, journey home &mdash; for a test whose most likely outcome is &ldquo;no change&rdquo;. Multiply that by every man on a surveillance list, for years, and the clinic is full of people who didn&apos;t need to be there.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="stage" id="act2">
    <div class="stage-side"><div class="stage-number">2</div><div class="stage-bar"></div></div>
    <div class="stage-main">
      <div class="scene"><img src="Assets/mark-stage2.png" alt="Mark at home confirming the order on his tablet" onerror="this.closest('.scene').style.display='none'"><div class="scene-cap">The order comes to Mark to confirm. The choice, the address and the timing stay his.</div></div>
      <div class="stage-eyebrow">His consultant orders</div>
      <h2 class="stage-title">Adam sets the intent. Mark confirms it. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="mark-a2"></span></h2>
      <p class="stage-body">Mark never sees a catalogue, never picks a supplier, never holds a contract. His consultant urologist identifies him from the active surveillance list and sets the intent to order. <strong>Mark confirms the order, the address and the timing</strong> &mdash; and that confirmation step repeats at every cycle, so the test never arrives unrequested or unexplained.</p>
      <p class="stage-body">The choice stays his. At the point of confirmation, Mark can still choose the in-person route &mdash; the home kit is an offer, not a conscription. He takes the kit.</p>
      <div class="benefits">
        <div class="benefit choice"><div class="b-num">His call</div><div class="b-label">Patient route choice preserved</div><div class="b-desc">At every cycle&apos;s confirmation the in-person route stays open. The home kit is an offer, never a conscription.</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="chips">
        <span class="chip">Clinician-initiated &middot; patient-confirmed</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="stage" id="act3">
    <div class="stage-side"><div class="stage-number">3</div><div class="stage-bar"></div></div>
    <div class="stage-main">
      <div class="scene"><img src="Assets/mark-stage3.png" alt="Mark taking the capillary sample at his kitchen table, his wife in the garden beyond" onerror="this.closest('.scene').style.display='none'"><div class="scene-cap">A capillary draw at the kitchen table. No car park, no waiting room, no needle in a clinic.</div></div>
      <div class="stage-eyebrow">Kit out, sample back</div>
      <h2 class="stage-title">A capillary draw at his kitchen table. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="mark-a3"></span></h2>
      <p class="stage-body">The kit arrives at the house &mdash; a capillary draw, not a full venous one. Mark takes the sample at home and returns it by Royal Mail to a specialist pathology lab. <strong>The result goes to his consultant first</strong>, reviewed in trend against every previous reading &mdash; not as a number in isolation, but as a line that is either flat or isn&apos;t.</p>
      <div class="pull-quote">
        <div class="pull-quote-text">&ldquo;The test comes to me. The consultant sees the result. They only call me if something needs to change.&rdquo;</div>
        <div class="pull-quote-attribution">Mark, 65 &mdash; on what surveillance feels like when it works</div>
      </div>
      <div class="benefits">
        <div class="benefit"><div class="b-num">&minus;1</div><div class="b-label">Hospital visit, every cycle</div><div class="b-desc">Car park, waiting room, needle, journey home &mdash; replaced by the kitchen table and Royal Mail. For life.</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="chips">
        <span class="chip kit">Kit logistics: capillary kit out &middot; Royal Mail back &middot; specialist lab &middot; result to the requesting clinician</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="interlude-wrap">
    <div class="interlude-photo"><img src="Assets/mark-interlude.png" alt="Mark and his wife walking together in the park" onerror="this.closest('.interlude-photo').style.display='none'"></div>
    <div class="interlude">
      <div class="interlude-eyebrow">Between the cycles</div>
      <div class="interlude-title">The silence is the service.</div>
      <div class="interlude-body">For a man on lifelong surveillance, the phone that doesn&apos;t ring is the whole point. No news doesn&apos;t mean nobody looked &mdash; it means somebody looked, in trend, against everything that came before, and the line is flat. Mark&apos;s retirement is not scheduled around phlebotomy appointments, and his cancer is watched more closely than it ever was in the waiting-room era. The result he doesn&apos;t hear about is the model working.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="stage" id="act4">
    <div class="stage-side"><div class="stage-number">4</div><div class="stage-bar"></div></div>
    <div class="stage-main">
      <div class="stage-eyebrow">Living on surveillance</div>
      <h2 class="stage-title">The cycle repeats. The list stays whole. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="mark-a4"></span></h2>
      <p class="stage-body">Every cycle runs the same way: intent from the surveillance list, confirmation from Mark, kit, sample, lab, trend review. Where a trust already runs a condition-specific tracker for scheduling and recall, HomeTest sits <strong>underneath</strong> it as the remote-delivery layer &mdash; the tracker stays the source of truth for cadence and clinical management. If Mark&apos;s PSA ever rises, escalation starts from a trend the team can see whole, and the clinic slot goes to the conversation that needs it.</p>
      <p class="stage-body">And beside Mark&apos;s cohort sit two more: a <strong>radiotherapy follow-up cohort</strong> (men in post-treatment PSA surveillance, watched for biochemical recurrence &mdash; a different clinical state from Active Surveillance, served by the same machinery), and a quieter one: <strong>men referred to Urology with elevated PSA but no cancer diagnosis</strong>, who currently fall between acute care and a GP contract that carries no obligation to monitor them. The same kit-and-trend machinery is the candidate answer for that monitoring gap. <span style="color:var(--amber-deep);font-weight:800;">&#9873;</span> prospective cohort, commissioning shape held open.</p>
      <div class="chips">
        <span class="chip">Sits underneath existing recall trackers</span>
        <span class="chip">Escalation only on trend change</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="dashboard">
    <div class="dashboard-eyebrow">What the surveillance list shows &middot; between escalations</div>
    <div class="dashboard-title">Mark &middot; PSA active surveillance &middot; watch, no action</div>
    <div class="dashboard-row">
      <div class="dashboard-card">
        <div class="dashboard-card-label">PSA trend &middot; four cycles</div>
        <div class="dashboard-metric flat">Flat</div>
        <div class="dashboard-metric-sub">no rise across two years of monitoring &mdash; the line that means &ldquo;no change&rdquo;</div>
        <div class="dashboard-chart"><svg viewBox="0 0 100 30" preserveAspectRatio="none"><polyline fill="none" stroke="#FFB91D" stroke-width="2.5" points="0,16 25,15 50,16 75,15 100,16"/></svg></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dashboard-card">
        <div class="dashboard-card-label">Routine clinic visits</div>
        <div class="dashboard-metric">0</div>
        <div class="dashboard-metric-sub">this year &middot; every draw done at the kitchen table, not in phlebotomy</div>
        <div class="dashboard-chart"><svg viewBox="0 0 100 30" preserveAspectRatio="none"><polyline fill="none" stroke="#5EBCDB" stroke-width="2.5" points="0,6 25,19 50,24 75,25 100,25"/></svg></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dashboard-card">
        <div class="dashboard-card-label">Escalation status</div>
        <div class="dashboard-metric">Watch</div>
        <div class="dashboard-metric-sub">no trend change &middot; no call needed &middot; the clinic slot stays free</div>
        <div class="dashboard-chart"><svg viewBox="0 0 100 30" preserveAspectRatio="none"><polyline fill="none" stroke="rgba(255,255,255,0.5)" stroke-width="2.5" points="0,16 25,16 50,16 75,16 100,16"/></svg></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="dashboard-footer">The line is flat, so nobody had to phone Mark and Mark didn&apos;t have to come in. <strong>Every cycle that stays flat is a clinic appointment that didn&apos;t need to happen</strong> &mdash; for Mark, and for every man on the surveillance list behind him.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="benefit-banner">
    <div class="bb-num">&minus;1</div>
    <div class="bb-text">
      <div class="bb-title">Hospital visit per test, for every man on the list, for as long as the list exists.</div>
      <div class="bb-desc">Routine draws move to kit-and-post; clinic time concentrates on the patients whose trend lines moved. <strong>Lifelong cohorts grow. Clinic capacity doesn&apos;t have to.</strong></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="outcomes">
    <div class="outcome">
      <div class="outcome-h">For Mark</div>
      <div class="outcome-title">Surveillance without the waiting room.</div>
      <div class="outcome-body">Routine monitoring happens at his kitchen table, on his calendar. He confirms every order, keeps the in-person option, and hears from his team <strong>when it matters</strong> &mdash; which is the only time anyone wants that call.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="outcome">
      <div class="outcome-h">For the care team</div>
      <div class="outcome-title">Trend lines, not snapshots.</div>
      <div class="outcome-body">Adam&apos;s surveillance list runs itself between escalations: results return in trend, recall stays with the existing tracker, and outpatient phlebotomy stops absorbing men whose most likely result is &ldquo;no change&rdquo;. Clinic time concentrates on the patients whose lines moved.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="outcome">
      <div class="outcome-h">For the system</div>
      <div class="outcome-title">A surveillance pathway that scales.</div>
      <div class="outcome-body">Lifelong cohorts grow; clinic capacity doesn&apos;t. Remote PSA monitoring moves the routine load to kit-and-post logistics and a specialist lab &mdash; and offers the <strong>monitoring-gap cohort</strong> a way to be monitored at all, rather than falling between two contracts.</div>
    </div>
